The facts of the death of Oppianicus, as referred to by Cicero, seem open to doubt: it will not escape a critical reader, for instance, that while secking to disprove the genuineness of the alleged depositions of Strato and Nicostratus, he nowhere definitely states what those depositions were.

The two minor charges of poisoning alleged against Cluentius need not detain us. The first Cicero refutes on the evidence of the senator Plaetorius, with whom the alleged vic'tim, Vibius CappadOX, was staying at the time of his death (ἓ 165). In reply to the second, he brings forward the father of the young Balbutius, who was said to have met his death by accidentally swallowing

‚ a poisoned draught which Cluentius was alleged to have prepared for Oppianicus the younger (ἓὲ 166-168). This last may, perhaps, be considered the only satisfactory piece of evidence in the whole speech. THE SCAMANDER INcmENT.
